{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/appendicitis/background-information/complications/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"949c28c0-203f-5e3d-9504-b0e2b0c140cc","slug":"complications","fullItemName":"Complications","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 2dbe2a3a-3a97-4503-a80f-f068fb064ed4 --><h2>What are the complications?</h2><!-- end field 2dbe2a3a-3a97-4503-a80f-f068fb064ed4 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item edb8a7e4-4544-4e66-bf3a-65aa5cd746b8 --><!-- begin field c6e2ea2b-905c-4406-a768-cd0beec96d58 --><p><strong>Appendicitis may be uncomplicated (non-perforating) or complicated (perforating) </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Bhangu, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Gorter, 2016</a>]<strong>.</strong></p><ul><li>Perforation is defined by a visible hole in the appendix, or an appendicolith (calcified deposit within the appendix) free within the abdomen [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Howell, 2018</a>]. The rate of perforation varies from 16–40%, with a higher frequency occurring in younger age groups and in people older than 50 years of age. Appendiceal perforation is associated with increased morbidity and mortality compared with non-perforating acute appendicitis, with a mortality rate of about 5% [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Di Saverio, 2020</a>].<ul><li>A consensus guideline states that elderly people are more at risk of vascular sclerosis of the appendix and narrowing of the lumen by fibrosis [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Fugazzola, 2020</a>].</li><li>Expert opinion in a review article notes that young children and those with increased duration of symptoms are at higher risk of perforation [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Howell, 2018</a>]. Similarly, an additional review article notes that risk factors for perforation include older age, three or more co-morbid conditions, and male sex. Time from symptom onset to diagnosis and surgery is directly associated with perforation risk. Furthermore, perforation may lead to an increased length of hospital stay, extended antibiotic administration, and more severe post-operative complications [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Synder, 2018</a>].</li></ul></li><li>A systematic review on the diagnosis of acute appendicitis notes that a delay or misdiagnosis of appendicitis can result in additional severe complications from perforation, such as abscess formation, sepsis, and intra-abdominal adhesions [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Kabir, 2017</a>]:<ul><li>Appendix mass — the inflamed appendix becomes walled off by omentum (a layer of peritoneum) and surrounding viscera to form an inflammatory mass [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Stringer, 2017</a>].</li><li>Appendix abscess — an appendix mass may resolve spontaneously or progress to form a localized abscess [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Gorter, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Di Saverio, 2020</a>].</li><li>Generalized peritonitis — a potentially life-threatening infection that results from the release of purulent material from a perforation into the peritoneal cavity [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Marzuillo, 2015</a>].</li><li>Sepsis — perforation can lead to sepsis and occurs in 17–32% of people with acute appendicitis [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Synder, 2018</a>]. See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/sepsis/\">Sepsis</a> for more information.</li><li>Bowel obstruction — may be a further complication of perforation, and may follow the development of intra-abdominal adhesions [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Kabir, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Synder, 2018</a>].</li></ul></li><li>In pregnancy, possible complications of acute appendicitis include an increased risk of fetal loss and pre-term delivery [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Baird, 2017</a>].</li></ul><!-- end field c6e2ea2b-905c-4406-a768-cd0beec96d58 --><!-- end item edb8a7e4-4544-4e66-bf3a-65aa5cd746b8 -->","topic":{"id":"34a7018e-bdb2-5fb9-8f39-14b87cb77872","topicId":"38888cc0-af2f-4224-93a9-2ffe35d3793c","topicName":"Appendicitis","slug":"appendicitis","lastRevised":"Last revised in July 2020","chapters":[{"id":"c3867ccc-2088-5ea2-a8b8-c8a8fa3b1495","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"cadf0862-729f-56ee-b5c8-c92c5a72cbb5","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"efd5c1ac-3b3a-5b2c-82d5-19cda81e37fe","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"5c0768a7-4653-5b13-9bdd-b0696c5ea29a","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"1c4d3384-d57f-500b-ac6c-5360cef5f665","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"665f1a5d-97d4-56f8-a6d9-9fccc1bb162b","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"2b7bc99